    "recap_headline": "University of North Carolina Athletics",
    "recap_text": "CHAPEL HILL, N.C.\n\u2013 The Diamond Heels continue through ACC play back in the friendly confines of Boshamer Stadium as Louisville comes to Chapel Hill for a weekend tilt.\nIt will be the third year in a row and the seventh all-time series between the two programs with UNC holding a 13-9 overall record. Last year the teams split a Friday double header before Louisville won on Sunday.\nThe two teams have defended their own turf well, each with a positive win percentage at home. The two neutral site matchups were split, a win for the Heels in Omaha in 2007 and one for the Cards in their first ever ACC tournament.\nSCHEDULE\nGame 1: Friday, Mar. 20 \u2013 8\u00a0PM \u2013\nACC Network\n\u2013\nLive Stats\nGame 2: Saturday, Mar. 21 \u2013 2 PM -\nACCNX\n\u2013\nLive Stats\nGame 3: Sunday, Mar. 22 \u2013 1 PM -\nACCNX\n\u2013\nLive Stats\nNo. 14 North Carolina Tar Heels (18-3-1)(4-2 ACC)\nHead Coach:\nScott Forbes\nRecord at UNC: 218-107-1\nRecord vs. Louisville: 8-4\nLouisville Cardinals (15-6)(2-1 ACC)\nHead Coach: Dan McDonnell\nRecord at Louisville: 808-365-1\nRecord vs. UNC: 9-11\nPROJECTED STARTERS\nFriday: RHP\nJason DeCaro\nvs. LHP Ethan Eberle\nSaturday: RHP\nRyan Lynch\nvs. LHP Wyatt Danilowicz\nSunday: LHP\nFolger Boaz\nvs. TBA\nSERIES HISTORY\nAll-Time: UNC 13-9\nCurrent Streak: L1\nChapel Hill: 9-2\nAway: 3-6\nNeutral Site: 1-1\nFirst Meeting: March 28, 1995\nAPPOINTMENT TELEVISION\n\u27a4 Friday's game will Carolina's first of the season to appear on linear TV. UNC is currently schedule for 10 cable network selections, nine on ACC Network and one appearance on ESPN2.\n\u27a4 Carolina sits tied with Clemson for the most selections in the conference.\n\u27a4 It is already the most TV slots in program history before you factor in \"Wildcard\" spots and postseason fixtures that could add to that number.\n\u27a4 Last season, the Heels held a 12-4 record in TV games and were 8-1 in the regular season in such fixtures.\nFULL CIRCLE FOR WINSLOW\n\u27a4 He may be new to the Heels, but his connections to this team run deep.\n\u27a4 Winslow spent the final two seasons of his high school career at Pro5 Academy under coach Sean Gallaher (Gavin's dad) while living with the Gallaher's throughout that time. Gavin and Macon are living with each other once again in Chapel Hill.\n\u27a4 Going even further back, Macon's father Leary played for Heels' assistant coach\nScott Jackson\nwhen \u00a0they were both at Barton.\nNO PLACE LIKE THE BOSH\n\u27a4 The Tar Heels have won 77.4 percent of their home games under\nScott Forbes\n, going 155-45-1.\n\u27a4 The 2025 squad racked up a 29-9 (.763) home record, winning five of seven series.\n\u27a4 The Tar Heels boasted a 37-3 record at Boshamer Stadium in 2024, winning a program record 92.5 percent of its games at home.\n\u27a4 It was the 13th time in program history the Tar Heels won 30 or more home games.\n\u27a4 Originally opened in 1972 before reopening in 2009 after a $26 million renovation, the Bosh has been the site for many magical memories. Since '09, the Heels have hosted 10 regionals and eight supers in their palace affectionately referred to as the \"Augusta National of College Baseball.\"",
    "watch_url": "https://www.espn.com/watch/player/_/id/ca111091-a3b8-4b35-b2c8-6c1681a54c57"
  },
